this is because I want to

00:01:00.611 --> 00:01:04.033
emphasize that this r,
the little r,

00:01:04.033 --> 00:01:06.689
what I've now written down as a
little r in this

00:01:06.689 --> 00:01:10.880
equation,
is not the radius of the object;

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:14.080
r is just a coordinate.

00:01:17.180 --> 00:01:20.253
It can be anything.
It's not the radius of the

00:01:20.253 --> 00:01:23.814
object for which the mass is
giving you the Schwarzschild

00:01:23.814 --> 00:01:26.843
radius.
The Schwarzschild radius is a

00:01:26.843 --> 00:01:30.891
very specific radius.
r_s =

00:01:30.891 --> 00:01:36.470
2GM / c^(2) so
that's a specific number.

00:01:36.470 --> 00:01:40.648
The little r, here,
is just a coordinate and so is

00:01:40.648 --> 00:01:44.900
φ and θ, which combine into
this thing which I've called

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:46.989
Omega [Ω]
and T.

00:01:46.989 --> 00:01:53.154
And so if you have an object of
mass M and radius--I'll

00:01:53.154 --> 00:01:58.004
give--I'll call that
R_0 just to

00:01:58.004 --> 00:02:03.966
make sure that you understand
that this is the radius of the

00:02:03.966 --> 00:02:05.280
object.

00:02:09.129 --> 00:02:13.330
The radius of the object
doesn't come into this metric.

00:02:13.330 --> 00:02:16.727
The mass does,
because the mass turns into the

00:02:16.727 --> 00:02:20.879
Schwarzschild radius and that's
part of the equation.

00:02:20.879 --> 00:02:23.740
But the radius of the object
doesn't matter.

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:26.479
And so, if you then ask,
well, what is a black hole?

00:02:26.479 --> 00:02:31.824
A black hole is something in
which the radius of the object

00:02:31.824 --> 00:02:35.509
is less than the Schwarzschild
radius.

00:02:35.509 --> 00:02:39.990
Because if that's true,
