00:45:18.580 --> 00:45:20.250
How are we doing?
Okay.

00:45:20.250 --> 00:45:26.980
Let me mention one last
post-Newtonian effect.

00:45:26.980 --> 00:45:32.880
This is post-Newtonian effect
number four.

00:45:32.880 --> 00:45:37.500
This is the existence of
gravitational waves.

00:45:41.230 --> 00:45:47.199
And the way this works is--let
me put these over here.

00:45:47.199 --> 00:45:50.762
Remember the bed sheet and the
basketball, over here,

00:45:50.762 --> 00:45:53.151
from a few days ago?
All right, now,

00:45:53.151 --> 00:45:56.562
imagine that that basketball,
which is some massive object,

00:45:56.562 --> 00:45:59.854
is moving back and forth on
the--it's orbiting some other

00:45:59.854 --> 00:46:02.639
thing on that bed sheet.
What will happen?

00:46:02.639 --> 00:46:07.078
Well, the bed sheet will ripple
in different ways as the thing

00:46:07.078 --> 00:46:09.658
moves around.
And this creates,

00:46:09.658 --> 00:46:12.810
essentially,
a wave of distortions of

00:46:12.810 --> 00:46:17.275
space-time that propagates
outward, as it turns out,

00:46:17.275 --> 00:46:22.885
at the speed of light.
So, the way this works is,

00:46:22.885 --> 00:46:29.626
as a mass moves back and
forth--perhaps because it's in

00:46:29.626 --> 00:46:35.835
orbit,
or for some other reason--it

00:46:35.835 --> 00:46:47.262
generates ripples in space-time.
These propagate outward at the

00:46:47.262 --> 00:46:51.302
speed of light.
And we'll talk later,

00:46:51.302 --> 00:46:54.240
maybe, about how one--what it
means to have a ripple in

00:46:54.240 --> 00:46:56.579
space-time, and how one might
detect it.

00:46:56.579 --> 00:47:04.158
But there's a more immediate
effect, which is that the energy

00:47:04.158 --> 00:47:11.863
in these so-called gravitational
waves--they carry energy with

00:47:11.863 --> 00:47:15.728
them.
And the energy comes from--is

00:47:15.728 --> 00:47:21.373
extracted from the orbit of the
object that's moving back and

00:47:21.373 --> 00:47:25.794
forth.
So, the orbit gradually loses

00:47:25.794 --> 00:47:30.936
energy.
And that means that the orbit

00:47:30.936 --> 00:47:34.519
gets smaller,
gradually.

00:47:34.519 --> 00:47:38.880
So, the orbit gets gradually
smaller.

00:47:38.880 --> 00:47:41.749
And so, in the Newtonian
approximation,

00:47:41.749 --> 00:47:45.978
things stay in orbit and
they're perfectly stable forever

00:47:45.978 --> 00:47:48.126
and ever,
and they just go orbiting

00:47:48.126 --> 00:47:49.619
around, and around,
and around.

00:47:49.619 --> 00:47:54.630
But, in general relativity,
there's a gradual,

00:47:54.630 --> 00:47:59.751
slow loss of energy,
and objects will gradually

00:47:59.751 --> 00:48:03.659
spiral in.
Now, this happens really slowly.

00:48:03.659 --> 00:48:07.159
It has not been detected in the
Solar System.

00:48:07.159 --> 00:48:09.406
That is to say,
even the orbit of Mercury,

00:48:09.406 --> 00:48:12.638
we can't measure its orbital
period accurately enough to see

00:48:12.638 --> 00:48:15.579
this slow down.
Certainly all the planets in

00:48:15.579 --> 00:48:19.310
the Solar System have been
happily going in their orbits

00:48:19.310 --> 00:48:22.905
for four-and-a-half billion
years with no sign of this

00:48:22.905 --> 00:48:27.893
effect.
But you can see this in certain

00:48:27.893 --> 00:48:33.780
kinds of binary stars.
Stars which happen to have very

00:48:33.780 --> 00:48:35.040
short orbits.

00:48:38.230 --> 00:48:43.475
And in particular,
there's something called the

00:48:43.475 --> 00:48:47.419
binary pulsar.
Pulsar is a kind of neutron

00:48:47.419 --> 00:48:50.384
star.
And these gravitational wave

00:48:50.384 --> 00:48:55.996
effects, the gradual decrease in
the orbit, has been observed in

00:48:55.996 --> 00:48:59.521
binary pulsars.
And we'll talk about that,

00:48:59.521 --> 00:49:00.854
I guess, next time.
 

